node.text:
More than the launch of unparalleled works of jewelry craft, @Bulgari's Magnifica High Jewelry collection is a celebration of rebirth. Honored through magnificent muses, music, and Milan, take a look at Bvlgari's latest high jewelry collection.
 
Models: @vittoria, @lilyaldridge @heconghc, @solangesmith and @blesnyaminher
Special Guests: @andreabocelliofficial @beatricevenezi
Project by @oma.eu
Director @tommaso.ottomano
DOP@ mrcodepa
Stylist @sagliogeraldine
Music @guazzonemarco 
Production @studio.april
#Bvlgari #BvlgariJewelry #BvlgariHighJewelry #BvlgariMagnifica #Milan

node.text: After making her #NYFW modeling debut at @ProenzaSchouler, @EllaEmhoff landed a knitwear collaboration with Batsheva Hay (@batshevadress). The 21-year-old student, model, and designer met up with Hay amid NYFW—and #GoodMorningVogue was there to capture their conversations about materials, fit, and texture, plus Ella's rise to fame in the wake of the inauguration of President Joe Biden and Emhoff’s step-mother, Kamala Harris, in January.

node.text: This month, Vogue joined forces with an army of photographers and models all around the globe—stable Zoom connections required, please!—and sent the best and brightest of the new collections via courier services everywhere from Beijing to Brazil, Lagos to Los Angeles. Our concept? Simple, glorious movement: After a year of stasis, immobility and lockdowns, we wanted to see spring fashion breaking free. These are the looks we love, shot by the photographers we adore, on the run and out for a walk, a swim, a dance. Tap the link in our bio to see more.

node.text:
Today, @KamalaHarris became the first woman of color ever sworn in as vice president of the United States.

To celebrate this moment, twelve young women discussing what it means to them to see a Black woman of Indian descent elected to the second-highest office in the land. “Every little girl sees that this is a country of possibility,” @KamalaHarris states in one address, and that sentiment is widely echoed. “She reminds me every day that I am capable and worthy of my wildest dreams,” says one participant.

Director @rombokob
Producer @aliwebb_producer
Casting Director: Rebecca Dealy
Archival Research: Manon Blackman
Editor @ann_lupo
GFX @horatiobaltz
Color @carlosfloresfilms
Mix @cstropko
Post Production @forager.tv

node.title: 12 Girls on What Kamala Harris Becoming Vice President Means to Them

node.text: Throughout the political tumult of 2020, @janayathefuture was one of the most prominent voices to become a source of healing and hope. Reflecting on this week’s events, Khan points out the lack of police presence at the Capitol, a fact that exposes, in their own words, “a clear double standard for how Black protestors have been treated over the past several years. What we know to be true is that there is a way that white rage is celebrated in this country and Black grief is criminalized.” To hear more, make sure to check out Khan’s Sunday Sermons, returning tomorrow 1/10  at 12PM PST on their account.

node.title: @janayathefuture on Moving Forward from the Capitol Riots

node.text:
In the two years before his death on September 3, 2019, famed photographer Peter Lindbergh self-curated his first exhibition, pulling more than 140 photographs from his extensive archive, dating from the early 1980s to the 2010s. Featuring unseen images of legendary supermodels, Peter Lindbergh: Untold Stories ran at the Museum Kunstpalast in Düsseldorf, Germany last year.

The outcome of Untold Stories epitomizes the photographer’s attitude to his work. Lindbergh was given free rein to select or veto images from his archive, without any outsider input. Finding himself at a loss and thinking that the project would never be finished, he restarted the process again and again, incorporating new images and rejecting others. But it was through this way of working that the photographer rediscovered a new connection to his work—one that emanates from his final project. 

On the anniversary of his death, we revisit and honor his final project at the link in our bio.

node.text:
One of the most extreme abortion laws in the U.S. since the landmark Roe v. Wade decision of 1973 went into effect after the Supreme Court failed to act on a request to block it. 

Texas’s Senate Bill 8, or S.B. 8, effectively bans abortions after six weeks for all but those in a life-threatening condition, making no exceptions in cases of rape or incest. It marks the latest chapter in an ongoing battle over reproductive rights within a state where abortion access is already severely limited.

S.B. 8 has also laid the groundwork for a legal Wild West that would all but force every abortion provider in the state to shut down immediately for fear of being overwhelmed with expensive ongoing courtroom battles. Many pro-life organizations are already launching tip lines where people seeking or who have undergone abortions can be reported to likeminded litigious vigilantes; and equally concerning is the broad array of people who could be targeted by these legal attacks. Beyond the organizations and physicians themselves, clinic nurses, abortion-fund workers, rape-crisis counselors, and even friends offering a car ride to an abortion clinic are at risk of being sued. 

In 2021, the fight for reproductive rights for every woman continues. For information on how to petition against the law or to support organizations and abortion-fund groups that will help patients leave Texas in order to receive care, you can find resources at the link in our bio, courtesy of the @ACLU_nationwide. Photographed by @cassblackbird.

node.text:
Broadway’s new season opens with three works by Black playwrights, one of them being Keenan Scott II’s Thoughts of a Colored Man (@coloredmanplay). 

@Keenanthemuse's clear-eyed and lyrical look at contemporary Black manhood offers a snapshot of 24 hours in the lives of seven Black men in Brooklyn’s Bedford-Stuyvesant neighborhood.

The ensemble cast, above, represent characters that chart a course through a gentrifying neighborhood and a society that sees them via a narrow and distorted lens, struggling with racial and sexual identity and ultimately transcending the labels they’ve been given. 

“Too often, Black men are portrayed as monoliths, based on stereotypes and tropes—the superathlete or the supercriminal,” Scott says. “With these seven men, I wanted to show the spectrum of Black male existence. I wanted to show each of them, and all of us, in our totality.”

Tap the link in our bio for more details. Video by @griff, styled by @maxortegag.

node.text:
As New York City’s summer of rebirth winds down and a new theater season is poised to kick off, it feels like the right moment to look back at what we’ve lost and ahead at what’s to come—including productions that signal the first glimmers of change on Broadway.

@CamilleABrown will bring a new production of "for colored girls who have considered suicide / when the rainbow is enuf," Ntozake Shange’s 1976 paean in poetry and dance to the vulnerability and resilience of Black women. 

Brown’s production, which will fuse theatrical elements, offers her unique interpretation of Shange’s vision of a unified “choreopoem” and will make her the first Black woman to both direct and choreograph a play on Broadway.

Tap the link in our bio for all of the details behind the production. Photographed by @mirandabarnes, styled by @maxortegag, Vogue, September 2021

Happy Birthday, @Zendaya!

Whether she’s in archival fashion or fresh-off-the-runway looks, Zendaya and her stylist @LuxuryLaw Roach consistently keep her fans on their toes.

In honor of her 25th birthday today, Vogue is looking back on some of her greatest recent style hits. Tap the link in our bio for more. Directed by @bardiazeinali, styled by @jordenbickham.
